04200nam a22006855i 9780292772045DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014046224  a97802927720457 a10.7560/7720382doi  a(DE-B1597)587236  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aHJ217b.P75 2015 4aHJ217b.P75 2015eb 7aHIS0020102bisacsh04a336.3/909385223  aNH 5850qOBV2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/125729:1 aPritchard, David M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPublic Spending and Democracy in Classical Athens /cDavid M. Pritchard. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illu strations -- tList of Tables -- tList of Abbreviations -- tPreface -- t1. Public-Spending Debates -- t2. The Cost of Festivals -- t3. The Cost of Democracy -- t4. The Cost of War -- t5. Conclusion: Public-Spending Priorities -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex of Sources -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn his On the Glory of Athens, Plutarch complained that the Athenian people spent more on the production of dramatic festivals and “the misfortunes of Medeas and Electras than they did on maintaining their empire and fighting for their liberty against the Persians.” This view of the Athenians’ misplaced priorities became orthodoxy with the publication of August Böckh’s 1817 book Die Staatshaushaltung der Athener [The Public Economy of Athens], which criticized the classical Athenian dēmo s for spending more on festivals than on wars and for levying unjust taxes to pay for their bloated government. But were the Athenians’ priorities really as misplaced as ancient and modern historians believed? Drawing on lines of evidence not available in Böckh’s time, Public Spending and Democracy in Classical Athens calculates the real costs of religion, politics, and war to settle the long-standing debate about what the ancient Athenians valued most highly. David M. Pritchard explains that, in Athenian democracy, voters had full control over public spending. When they voted for a bill, they always knew its cost and how much they normally spent on such bills. Therefore, the sums they chose to spend on festivals, politics, and the armed forces reflected the order of the priorities that they had set for their state. By calculating these sums, Pritchard convincingly demonstrates that it was not religion or politics but war that was the overriding priority of the Athenian people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDemocracyzGreecezAthensxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aFinance, PubliczGreecezAthensxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWar and societyzGreecezAthensxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWarxEconomic aspectszGreecezAthensxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77203840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292772045423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292772045/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK